{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "05 ‚Äî The Turn Pipeline: One Spine for Every Gateway",
  "description": "internal/turn is the channel-agnostic spine every gateway calls: context assembly, the agent loop, the honesty check, and persistence ‚Äî all in one place, once. The web chat endpoint and the CLI both invoke turn.Run; they only differ in how they render the event stream. This tour follows a single owner turn from boundary to persisted record, touching the RecentTurnWindow context budget, tool-set assembly, the verify honesty check, OriginUncommitted quarantine, and the heads persona model.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/turn/turn.go",
      "line": 69,
      "title": "5.1 ‚Äî The turn boundary: one function for all gateways",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Run(ctx context.Context, app core.App, client llm.Client, userText string, emit func(agent.Event)) (Result, error)\n```\n\n`turn.Run` is the enforcer of the AGENTS.md rule: *gateways adapt; they never re-implement*. The web chat handler (`internal/web/chat.go`) and the CLI (`internal/cli`) both call this one function. The only thing they own is what they do with each `agent.Event` ‚Äî flush a Datastar SSE patch, or print a JSON envelope.\n\nEverything that makes a turn trustworthy ‚Äî context limits, tool selection, the honesty check, durable persistence ‚Äî lives here and runs exactly the same way regardless of which surface carried the message. That is what makes one surface's output trustworthy evidence about another's.\n\n`emit` is the gateway's hook: it may be nil (the function substitutes a no-op), so callers that only want the Result and don't need streaming can pass nil.\n\n**Tour 07** covers the web gateway that calls this. **Tour 10** covers the CLI gateway."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/turn/turn.go",
      "line": 32,
      "title": "5.2 ‚Äî Context is not persistence: the RecentTurnWindow",
      "description": "```go\n// RecentTurnWindow caps how many prior text turns enter the model context.\n// Persistence is unbounded; context is not (the master-conversation\n// footgun defusal ‚Äî see internal/conversation).\nconst RecentTurnWindow = 20\n```\n\nPersistence and context are deliberately separated. Every turn is appended to the `messages` collection ‚Äî the full record lives in SQLite forever. But the model never sees the full history; only the last 20 text turns (plus a rolling compaction summary and a today block) enter each request.\n\nWithout this cap a long-lived conversation would quietly grow the context window until requests fail or become expensive. The cap is set here, once, so it cannot drift between gateways.\n\nThe context assembly block (lines 75‚Äì103) makes the structure explicit:\n1. **System prompt** ‚Äî the base Balaur persona + the active head's flavor + the present-moment anchor + today's task block + the knowledge/memory block + the compaction summary\n2. **Recent 20 turns** ‚Äî loaded by `conversation.RecentTurns` with `CompactedThrough` so already-compacted turns are excluded\n3. **This user turn** ‚Äî appended last so it is the freshest thing the model reads\n\nThe user message is persisted to SQLite *before* this block, but deliberately excluded from `recent` ‚Äî `RecentTurns` is called before `conversation.Append`.\n\n**Tour 12** covers the conversation package and compaction in depth."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent.go",
      "line": 84,
      "title": "5.3 ‚Äî Driving the loop",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (l *Loop) Run(\n    ctx context.Context,\n    history []llm.Message,\n    emit func(Event),\n) ([]llm.Message, error)\n```\n\nOnce context is assembled, `turn.Run` creates an `agent.Loop` and calls its `Run` method:\n\n```go\nloop := &agent.Loop{Client: client, Tools: ToolsForHead(app, head.Groups), MaxSteps: maxSteps(), Logger: app.Logger()}\nfinal, runErr := loop.Run(ctx, history, emit)\nres.Turn = final[contextLen:]\n```\n\nThe loop drives the `messages ‚Üí model ‚Üí tool calls ‚Üí tool results ‚Üí model ‚Ä¶` cycle until the model produces a plain-text answer or hits the step cap. It emits `agent.Event` values for every observable action ‚Äî text tokens, tool starts, tool results, errors ‚Äî which the gateway's `emit` renders live.\n\n`res.Turn = final[contextLen:]` slices off the input context so `res.Turn` holds only the new messages the loop appended this turn. That slice is what gets persisted.\n\n`maxSteps()` reads `BALAUR_MAX_STEPS` from the environment ‚Äî raised for self-development sessions that legitimately need more rounds (read, edit, build, verify).\n\n**Tour 03** covers the agent loop internals step by step."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/turn/tools.go",
      "line": 22,
      "title": "5.4 ‚Äî Composing the tool set",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Tools(app core.App) []agent.Tool\n```\n\n`Tools` assembles the full registry for the main (unrestricted) head. The assembly order is intentional and documented in the comment:\n\n1. Knowledge tools (always on ‚Äî they only *propose* memories, the consent boundary is in the approval flow)\n2. Task, life, journal tools (always on ‚Äî owner-consented by nature)\n3. Choice and UI tools (interaction primitives)\n4. Heads and profile management (reversible, audited config)\n5. OS tools ‚Äî **opt-in only**: `BALAUR_OS_ACCESS=1` must be set; the four OS tools (read, write, edit, bash) ship disabled\n6. `propose_extension` (proposing is consent-safe; running requires approval)\n7. Approved balaur-extensions, **collision-guarded**: the `taken` map prevents an extension from shadowing a built-in name\n8. `self` last ‚Äî so the capability inventory it reports matches the registry that actually shipped this turn\n\nThe collision guard is the key safety property:\n```go\ntaken := map[string]bool{\"self\": true}\nfor _, t := range ts {\n    taken[t.Spec.Name] = true\n}\nts = append(ts, ext.Tools(app, taken)...)\n```\n\nAn extension can never replace a built-in or the self tool by claiming the same name ‚Äî the `ext.Tools` call skips any name already in `taken`.\n\n**Tour 16** covers the extension sandbox. **Tour 17** covers the tool surface."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/turn/tools.go",
      "line": 69,
      "title": "5.5 ‚Äî Head filtering: capability groups",
      "description": "```go\nfunc ToolsForHead(app core.App, groups []string) []agent.Tool\n```\n\nWhen the active head has no groups (the main Balaur head), this calls `Tools(app)` and returns the full set. When a head declares groups, it assembles a narrower set:\n\n```go\nts := tools.ChoiceTools(app)\nts = append(ts, tools.UITools(app)...)\nts = append(ts, tools.HeadsTools(app)...)\nts = append(ts, tools.ProfileTools(app)...)\n\nif sel[\"memory\"] { ts = append(ts, tools.KnowledgeTools(app)...) }\nif sel[\"tasks\"]  { ts = append(ts, tools.TaskTools(app)...)     }\n...\n```\n\nHeads/profile tools are always included, regardless of groups. The comment explains why: they are *meta-capability*, not a privilege grant ‚Äî a scoped head still needs to be able to switch back and manage identity.\n\nThe six group keys (`memory`, `tasks`, `life`, `journal`, `os`, `extensions`) mirror the `heads.Groups` variable in `internal/heads/heads.go`. The built-in specialist heads use these: Scholar gets `[\"memory\"]`; Planner gets `[\"tasks\", \"memory\"]`; Coach gets `[\"journal\", \"life\", \"memory\"]`.\n\n**This is a capability filter, not a security boundary** ‚Äî the comment says so explicitly. The returned tools still run with the owner's full trust. Step 5.8 of this tour covers why.\n\nCross-reference: **Tour 17** for the tool constructors; **Tour 05, step 5.8** for the heads persona model."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/verify/verify.go",
      "line": 46,
      "title": "5.6 ‚Äî The honesty check: verify, don't trust",
      "description": "```go\nfunc CaptureSucceeded(turn []llm.Message) bool\nfunc ClaimsCapture(text string) bool\n```\n\nSmall models lie politely. A model trained to be helpful will often write \"Setting it now\" or \"Task saved\" without calling any tool ‚Äî a confident, plausible, and false statement. The package comment is blunt about this:\n\n> *small models lie politely (\"Setting it now\") without calling any tool*\n\nThe honesty check in `turn.Run` catches this deterministically, with no extra model judgment:\n\n```go\nif runErr == nil && !verify.CaptureSucceeded(res.Turn) && verify.ClaimsCapture(verify.LastAssistantText(res.Turn)) {\n    // one self-repair pass\n    retryBase := append(final, llm.Message{Role: \"user\", Content: verify.Correction})\n    if final2, retryErr := loop.Run(ctx, retryBase, emit); retryErr == nil {\n        res.Turn = append(res.Turn, final2[len(retryBase):]...)\n    }\n    if !verify.CaptureSucceeded(res.Turn) && verify.ClaimsCapture(verify.LastAssistantText(res.Turn)) {\n        res.CheckNote = verify.Note\n    }\n}\n```\n\n`CaptureSucceeded` checks whether any capture tool (`task_add`, `log_entry`, `journal_write`, etc.) returned a non-error result. `ClaimsCapture` runs regex patterns against the assistant's reply to detect affirmative capture language.\n\nIf the model claimed a capture but no tool ran: the pipeline injects `verify.Correction` as a synthetic user turn and reruns the loop ‚Äî one self-repair pass. The Correction message is scaffolding; it is never persisted. If the model still claims without doing, `res.CheckNote = verify.Note` ‚Äî a plain owner-facing note is recorded instead.\n\nThe `ClaimsCapture` patterns are precision-tuned: offers and questions (`\"want me to\"`, `\"shall I\"`) are excluded so a polite offer never triggers a false positive."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/turn/turn.go",
      "line": 124,
      "title": "5.7 ‚Äî Persistence and the OriginUncommitted quarantine",
      "description": "The persistence block (lines 124‚Äì164) appends every message the loop produced to the `messages` collection in PocketBase. Most messages get `origin = \"\"` (the normal path). The exception is the `OriginUncommitted` quarantine:\n\n```go\nif res.CheckNote != \"\" && m.Role == \"assistant\" && m.Content != \"\" {\n    origin = conversation.OriginUncommitted\n}\n```\n\nWhen the honesty check found an unbacked claim ‚Äî the model said \"Task saved\" but no tool ran ‚Äî the assistant turn is still written to SQLite (the owner's record is complete), but `RecentTurns` excludes `OriginUncommitted` messages when assembling future context.\n\nThis prevents a failure from compounding: if the model reads its own \"Task saved\" in the next turn's context, it learns to repeat the pattern. Quarantining the message breaks the feedback loop while keeping the full audit trail intact.\n\nThe `CheckNote` message (the owner-facing correction) is persisted separately with `origin = \"check\"` so it also appears in the conversation but is visually distinguishable.\n\nAGENTS.md rule: *Audit strictly AFTER the successful write, never before ‚Äî the audit log must not record a mutation that did not persist.* The loop touches memories here too:\n```go\nfor _, m := range usedMemories {\n    knowledge.Touch(app, knowledge.Memory, m)\n}\n```\nMemory records that informed this turn have their `last_used` timestamp updated ‚Äî after the write, not before."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/heads/heads.go",
      "line": 27,
      "title": "5.8 ‚Äî Personas, not sandboxes: the Head type",
      "description": "```go\ntype Head struct {\n    ID      string\n    Name    string\n    Purpose string\n    Avatar  string\n    Groups  []string\n    BuiltIn bool\n}\n```\n\nA `Head` is an identity: a name, a system-prompt flavor (`Purpose`), a Balaur avatar, and an optional capability-group filter. The package comment is explicit about what heads are not:\n\n> *It is a capability filter, NOT a security boundary ‚Äî see docs/superpowers/specs/2026-06-14-heads-as-personas-design.md.*\n\nAll turns run on behalf of the one owner. There is no per-head data scoping, no row-level security, no sandbox. Switching heads changes the voice, the avatar, and the subset of tools offered ‚Äî nothing about trust or data access changes. The tools a scoped head receives still run with the owner's full trust (as `ToolsForHead` documents).\n\nBuilt-in heads live in the `builtins` slice (code, not database rows). The owner can add custom heads as records in the `heads` collection. Either way, `Active(app)` resolves the current head from `owner_settings` and falls back to the main Balaur head if the setting is missing or points at a deleted record ‚Äî making persona switching gracefully reversible with no broken state.\n\nSwitching is audited: `tools.HeadsTools` always appears in the active tool set (it is always-on core in `ToolsForHead`), and every head switch goes through `heads.SetActive` which writes an `owner_settings` record ‚Äî a durable, inspectable fact in SQLite."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/heads/heads.go",
      "line": 83,
      "title": "5.9 ‚Äî Active: safe fallback by design",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Active(app core.App) Head {\n    id := store.GetOwnerSetting(app, activeHeadSetting, MainKey)\n    if h, ok := Find(app, id); ok {\n        return h\n    }\n    main, _ := Find(app, MainKey)\n    return main\n}\n```\n\n`Active` is called at the top of every `turn.Run` ‚Äî it must never panic or return a zero value. The two-level fallback guarantees this:\n\n1. Read `active_head` from `owner_settings`. If unset, the default argument `MainKey` (`\"balaur\"`) is returned by `GetOwnerSetting`.\n2. Try to `Find` that id. If found (built-in key or existing record), return it.\n3. If not found ‚Äî the owner deleted a custom head while it was active, or a bad value snuck in ‚Äî silently fall back to the main Balaur head.\n\nThe result is that Balaur always has a valid, well-defined persona. A deleted head never causes a 500 error; the next turn just runs as the default.\n\nThis is the same pattern the store seam uses for all owner settings: `GetOwnerSetting(app, key, defaultValue)` returns the default when the key is absent, so callers never have to handle the missing-key case explicitly. AGENTS.md names this the *store seam for cross-cutting concerns*.\n\n**Tour 12** covers `internal/store` and the owner settings seam. **Tour 05, step 5.5** covers how `head.Groups` flows into `ToolsForHead`."
    }
  ]
}
